Ok jackasses. As anyone with any type of cracking skills will tell you. KeyGens are tagged by most virus protectors as being a trojan or virus. 99% of the time, it lists as a trojan. Why this is? I don't know, I don't program anti-virus. The best thing to do is run the virus scan on the actual program, leaving out the keygen. You can google serials for most programs anyway. Furthermore, just downloading a virus won't do anything until it is "triggered". Sometimes, running a virus scan on a virus will set it off. like the Ali virus. It downloads within a program then once it's triggered, usually by Norton anti-virus, then it changes you settings to resemble win 95, connects to the internet and downloads every known trojan out there. So, if you are pissed that your "protection" is giving a warning, just be thankful that you didn't trigger it.
